         <div xml:id="main">
            <head type="incipit">
               <supplied reason="XTF-compatibility">Melbourne bot Garden ¶ 24/12/64. ¶ Dear Sir. ¶  ¶ I have to reply to your letter of the 12 Oct., ¶  arrived within the last week. The receipt of the proof sheets of the second vol. of the flora Austra...</supplied>
            </head>
            <p rend="number" xml:lang="en">64.12.24</p>
            <p rend="correspondent" xml:lang="en">To George Bentham</p>
            <p rend="location" xml:lang="en">RBG Kew, Kew correspondence, Australia, Mueller, 1858-70. ff. 155-7.</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; text-align: end; "
               xml:lang="en">Melbourne bot Garden</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; text-align: end; "
               xml:lang="en">24/12/64.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">Dear Sir.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>I have to reply to your letter of the 12 Oct.,<note xml:id="ftn1" type="footnote" n="1">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">G. Bentham to M, 12 October 1864.</p>
               </note> arrived within the last week. The receipt of the proof sheets of the second vol. of the flora Austral I was glad to acknowledge by last mail,<note xml:id="ftn2" type="footnote" n="2">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">Bentham (1863-78), vol. 2. The next earliest complete letter to Bentham surviving at Kew is dated 24 September 1864.</p>
               </note> when and in mails before I offered some notes thereon. <name key="Bryophyllum%20calycinum">Bryophyllum calycinum</name> is omitted in <name key="Crassulaceae">Crassulaceae</name>. I have not seen it myself but Dr Hooker must have some authentic record of this plant as an Australian, since he enumerates it in his list of Indo-Australian vegetation, prefixed to the flora Tasmanica.<note xml:id="ftn3" type="footnote" n="3">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">J. Hooker (1860), 'Introductory essay', p. cliv, <seg style="">also published separately as J. Hooker (1859a)</seg>.</p>
               </note>
            </p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>It will not be necessary to forward in future any more copies of the flor. Austr. to Copenhagen, to Beckler or to any other place on my behalf, as I formerly desired,<note xml:id="ftn4" type="footnote" n="4">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">See M to G. Bentham, 24 June 1863, and M to G. Bentham, 24 September 1863.</p>
               </note> in as much as I am under no obligation to the recipients and find the distribution of works, maintained by me out of my private means for many years too ruinous to be continued. I fear, that for this reason I must also limit for the present the subscription to the genera plantarum<note xml:id="ftn5" type="footnote" n="5">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">Bentham &amp; Hooker (1862-83).</p>
               </note> to two copies; The small saldo I owe you I will send either by this or next mail.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>I am thankful for the return of the <name key="Thalamiflora">Thalamiflora</name>, which you have arranged. It is always hindersome to be deprived of any part of a collection.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>I cannot well comprehend, how <name key="Myrtaceae">Myrtaceae</name> &amp; <name key="Compositae">Compositae</name> will find room with sundry smaller orders in one volume of the work. Even if <name key="Lythraceae">Lythraceae</name>, <name key="Passifloreae">Passifloreae</name>, <name key="Cucurbitaceae">Cucurbitaceae</name>, <name key="Homalineae">Homalineae</name>, <name key="Onagreae">Onagreae</name>, <name key="Melastomeae">Melastomeae</name>, <name key="Mesembryanthemeae">Mesembryanthemeae</name> had gone into the second volume, I do not think the two great f[amil]ies and the unseparable <name key="Rubiaceae">Rubiaceae</name>, <name key="Umbelliferae">Umbelliferae</name>, <name key="Araliaceae">Araliaceae</name>, <name key="Loranthaceae">Loranthaceae</name>, <name key="Caprifoliaceae">Caprifoliaceae</name> could be brought into one volume, with a prospect of giving so much of their characteristic, as to do justice to them.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>I anticipate, that you will find, <name key="Myrtaceae">Myrtaceae</name> &amp; the orders thence to <name key="Compositae">Compositae</name> will fully cover all pages of vol III &amp; that the latter order has to be retained for the fourth volume; if <name key="Euphorbiaceae">Euphorbiaceae</name>, which are ill placed in <name key="Monochlamydeae">Monochlamydeae</name> &amp; which will have gone through J. Muellers hands before you can have finished the <name key="Myrtaceae">Myrtaceae</name>, were accepted for the 3 vol. it would make a good complex without the <name key="Compositae">Compositae</name>. —</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Pray let me be informed, whether you desire the <name key="Euphorbiaceae">Euphorbiaceae</name> for the <name key="Calyciflorae">Calyciflorae</name> or rather for the <name key="Monochlamydeae">Monochlamydeae</name>. I have seemingly a new <name key="Kennedya">Kennedya</name>, distinct from K. bracteata. - <name key="Hardenbergia">Hardenbergia</name>, <name key="Physolobium">Physolobium</name> &amp; <name key="Zichya">Zichya</name> have to be regarded as mere subgenera of <name key="Kennedya">Kennedya</name>.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>The sum for the draft for vol II (£100) must be in your hands by this time. Your remarks about <name key="Glycyrrhiza">Glycyrrhiza</name> are interesting I am glad that case N. 14 arrived, but remain quite in incertainty about some of the others. As they have a consecutive number, perhaps you will kindly let me know what arrived</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>I regret, that your zealous &amp; valuable assistant Mr Black<note xml:id="ftn6" type="footnote" n="6">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">Alan A. Black.</p>
               </note> had to leave the chilly climate of England, for the same reason, which brought me to Australia. I trust he will be benefitted by the fine upland air of India.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>By my last letter I mentioned, that the 30 copies of the flor. Austral. had arrived &amp; they have been distributed by Government.<note xml:id="ftn7" type="footnote" n="7">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">Letter not found. The previous letter to Bentham in the files is dated 24 September 1864, at which time the printing of the second volume of <seg style="font-style: italic; ">Flora australiensis</seg> was being completed (See J. Hooker to M, 19 September 1864). The completed volumes had been sent by 12 October (G. Bentham to M, 12 October 1864).</p>
               </note>
            </p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>I shall commence the next number of the Fragmenta with a new genus of <name key="Tiliaceae">Tiliaceae</name> (<name key="Michiea">Michiea</name>)<note xml:id="ftn8" type="footnote" n="8">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">M erected five new genera in B65.04.01, not including <seg style="font-style: italic; ">
                        <name key="Michiea">Michiea</name>
                     </seg>, which he had erected in B64.05.01 (<seg style="font-style: italic; ">M. symphyanthera</seg>, p. 96). None of these genera is in <name key="Tiliaceae">Tiliaceae</name>. M did not publish any species in <name key="Tiliaceae">Tiliaceae</name> in 1865.</p>
               </note> closely allied to <name key="Glyphaea">Glyphaea</name>.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>It is quite possible that a few cultivated plants have slipped into the Sydney Collections, but as so many of these specimens are unnamed it is difficult for me to ascertain this.</p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: 0in; "
               xml:lang="en">With a cordial</p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: 0in; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Adieu</p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: 0in; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>yr</p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: 0in; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Ferd Mueller</p>
